From: PS3 Custom Toolchain <noreply@example.invalid>
Subject: [PATCH] dirent.h: guard `int dirfd(DIR *);` against macro collision

Our PS3-custom `<sys/dirent.h>` (added by an earlier patch in this
series) defines `dirfd` as a function-style macro — `#define dirfd(dp)
((dp)->dd_fd)` — so callers that include `<sys/dirent.h>` directly (or
indirectly via `<dirent.h>`) get the zero-cost `dp->dd_fd` read.

FreeBSD-derived `<dirent.h>` then declares `int dirfd(DIR *);` as a
plain function prototype.  The preprocessor expands the identifier
against our macro first, yielding `int ((DIR *)->dd_fd);` — a syntax
error at the dirent.h include site for any TU that transitively pulls
it in (observed while building Sony samples/common/gcmutil/snaviutil.cpp
against our SDK).

Fix: guard the prototype with `#ifndef dirfd`.  When the macro is
active (our PS3 configuration), the prototype is skipped and user
calls resolve against the macro expansion.  On a hypothetical target
that ships a real `dirfd()` function and doesn't define the macro,
the prototype is preserved untouched.

Signed-off-by: PS3 Custom Toolchain <noreply@example.invalid>
---
 newlib/libc/include/dirent.h | 2 ++
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+)

diff --git a/newlib/libc/include/dirent.h b/newlib/libc/include/dirent.h
--- a/newlib/libc/include/dirent.h
+++ b/newlib/libc/include/dirent.h
@@ -45,7 +45,9 @@
 __BEGIN_DECLS
 #if __MISC_VISIBLE || __POSIX_VISIBLE >= 200809 || __XSI_VISIBLE >= 700
 int	 alphasort(const struct dirent **, const struct dirent **);
+#ifndef dirfd
 int	 dirfd(DIR *);
+#endif
 #endif
 #if __BSD_VISIBLE
 int	 fdclosedir(DIR *);
